Part (d)

Even though summary statistics like the sum of squares and product matrix and variance and covariance matrix are helpful to understand the pattern of data but visualization is necessary to understand the distribution. We saw this with Anscombe’s Quartet in the previous problem set when data had the same summary statistics but vastly different distributions. Therefore, analysis would not be complete without looking at this data’s visualization.

Part (c)

The covariability between Year and Approval rating is negative, because looking at the graph we can see a negative gradient or a slope. Also there is more data point on the upper left quadrant and bottom right quadrant, make the graph negative.

Part (d)

The covariability between Approval and Margin will have the strongest covariability, because from the graph we can see a positive gradient and the number of data points on the left bottom quadrant and the upper right quadrant is more than the other quadrants. Hence the direction of the graph is also prositive.

Part (e)

corr<-cor(Approval)
corr
##                Year   Approval     Margin
## Year      1.0000000 -0.5420676 -0.6132944
## Approval -0.5420676  1.0000000  0.8842433
## Margin   -0.6132944  0.8842433  1.0000000
# Insert code or written answer here

Part (f)

From the correlation matrix we can see that the correction is mostly positive and strong between the Approval and the approval. However, in part f we mentioned that the strongest correlation is between Aprroval and Margin. The most negative and weakest correlation would be between the Year and margin.
